20 SECTION 3. IC 22-1-1-24 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
21 AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
22 1, 2026]: Sec. 24. (a) The following definitions apply throughout
23 this section:
24 (1) "Health care employee" has the meaning set forth in
25 IC 35-42-2-1.
26 (2) "School employee" has the meaning set forth in
27 IC 35-42-2-1.
28 (3) "Workplace battery" means a battery described in
29 IC 35-42-2-1(d) or IC 35-42-2-1(g).
30 (b) The employer of a health care employee or school employee
31 shall make a workplace battery report as described in subsection
32 (c) to the commissioner if a health care employee or school
33 employee is the victim of workplace battery.
34 (c) Beginning July 1, 2027, the employer shall make the
35 workplace battery report required under subsection (b) each year
36 before:
37 (1) August 1, for the period from January 1 to June 30; and
38 (2) February 1, for the period from July 1 to December 31.
39 The report shall be made on a form provided by the commissioner.
40 (d) The workplace battery report must include the following
41 information:
42 (1) The name of the employer.
EH 1040—LS 6292/DI 106

12
1 (2) The city and county in which a workplace battery was
2 committed.
3 (3) The time period covered by the report (January 1 to June
4 30 or July 1 to December 31).
5 (4) The number of workplace batteries that were committed
6 during the reporting period.
7 (5) The job title of each health care employee or school
8 employee who was the victim of the workplace battery.
9 (6) The date of each workplace battery.
10 (7) The address and specific location (such as "hospital
11 emergency room" or "school parking lot") where the
12 workplace battery occurred. However, if the battery occurred
13 at the health care employee's or school employee's home, the
14 report may not include the address.
15 (8) The circumstances surrounding the workplace battery and
16 any resulting injury, including the following, if known:
17 (A) The gender of the victim.
18 (B) The specific manner in which the workplace battery
19 was committed (such as by striking, biting, pushing,
20 kicking, use of an object, or use of a weapon).
21 (C) Whether the victim required hospitalization.
22 (D) If a weapon or other object was used to commit the
23 workplace battery, the type of weapon or object.
24 (E) Whether law enforcement was contacted or responded
25 to the workplace battery.
26 (F) Whether criminal charges were filed against the
27 perpetrator.
28 For a workplace battery that does not occur on the employer's
29 premises, the employer shall provide as much information as is
30 known to the employer.
31 (e) The employer shall make the report required under this
32 section regardless of whether a person is criminally charged with
33 the workplace battery.
