32 certification.
33 (e) A charitable bail certification is valid for two (2) years from the
34 date of issuance and may be renewed upon payment of a renewal fee
35 of three hundred dollars ($300). If a person applies for renewal before
36 the expiration of the existing certification, the existing certification
37 remains valid until the commissioner renews the certification, or until
38 five (5) days after the commissioner denies the application for renewal.
39 A person is entitled to renewal unless the commissioner denies the
40 application for renewal under subsection (f).
41 (f) The commissioner shall deny, suspend, revoke, or refuse to
42 renew certification for any of the following causes:
EH 1040—LS 6292/DI 106

14
1 (1) Any cause for which issuance of the certification could have
2 been refused had it then existed and been known to the
3 commissioner.
4 (2) Violation of any laws of this state in the course of dealings
5 under the certification.
6 (3) Material misstatement, misrepresentation, or fraud in
7 obtaining the certification.
8 (4) Misappropriation, conversion, or unlawful withholding of
9 money belonging to donors or others and received in the conduct
10 of business under the certification.
11 (5) Fraudulent or dishonest practices in the conduct of business
12 under the certification.
13 (6) Willful failure to comply with or willful violation of any
14 proper order or rule of the commissioner.
15 (7) When, in the judgment of the commissioner, the certificate
16 holder has, in the conduct of affairs under the certification,
17 demonstrated:
18 (A) incompetency or untrustworthiness;
19 (B) conduct or practices rendering the certificate holder unfit
20 to carry on charitable bail activities or making the certificate
21 holder's continuance detrimental to the public interest; or
22 (C) that the certificate holder is no longer in good faith
23 carrying on as a charitable bail organization;
24 and for these reasons is found by the commissioner to be a source
25 of detriment, injury, or loss to the public.
26 (8) The listing of the name of the applicant or certificate holder on
27 the most recent tax warrant list supplied to the commissioner by
28 the department of state revenue.
29 (g) A charitable bail organization must comply with all of the
30 following:
31 (1) If the charitable bail organization pays, or intends to pay, bail
32 for more than three (3) individuals in any one hundred eighty
33 (180) day period, the charitable bail organization must be certified
34 by the commissioner under this section before soliciting or
35 accepting donations for bail for another person, and before
36 depositing money for bail for another person.
37 (2) A charitable bail organization may not pay bail for a defendant
38 who:
39 (A) is charged with a crime of violence; or
40 (B) is charged with a felony and has a prior conviction for a
41 crime of violence.
42 (3) A charitable bail organization may not execute a surety bond
EH 1040—LS 6292/DI 106

15
1 for a defendant.
2 (4) A charitable bail organization shall, before paying bail for an
3 individual, execute an agreement described in IC 35-33-8-3.2
4 allowing the court to retain all or a part of the bail to pay publicly
5 paid costs of representation and fines, costs, fees, and restitution
6 that the court may order the defendant to pay if the defendant is
7 convicted.
8 (5) A charitable bail organization may not charge a premium or
9 receive any consideration for acting as a charitable bail
10 organization.
11 (h) All fees collected under this section must be deposited in the
12 bail bond enforcement and administration fund created by
13 IC 27-10-5-1.
14 (i) Any authorized employee of a charitable bail organization may
15 only deposit cash bail to the court.
16 (j) If an individual fails to appear, the bail shall be forfeited in the
17 manner described in IC 35-33-8-7 and the court shall take the steps
18 described in IC 35-33-8-8.
